  <section class="section">
    <div class="wrap narrow">
      <h2>Common Hobart failure modes — what our techs actually fix</h2>
      <p>
        Across the AM16 and LXe populations we see most often in LA, the most common service calls concentrate
        in a predictable set. The rinse-arm spray bearing is the number-one AM16 failure — under continuous
        rotation, the bearing wears, the arm starts to wobble, rinse-water coverage drops, and you see film on
        glassware coming out of the final rinse. Replacement is a 30-minute job if the part is on the truck.
      </p>
      <p>
        Booster heater contactors are second. Hobart door machines rely on a 180°F final-rinse booster to sanitize
        wares — when the contactor arcs out, the booster doesn't fire, rinse water drops below 180°F, and
        sanitation compliance fails. Operators notice because wares come out warmer, not steaming hot. Contactor
        replacement is 40 minutes. Third is the chemical dispenser solenoid — detergent or rinse-aid dispenser
        proportioning valve drifts or sticks, and you see either excessive suds, no rinse aid, or chemistry out
        of spec on the wash cycle.
      </p>
      <p>
        On the LXe undercounter line, door gaskets are the single most common part we replace. The magnetic-strip
        gasket on an undercounter door compresses over 18–24 months of heavy bar service; once the seal is
        compromised, the unit loses temperature during the wash cycle and operators notice the cycle times
        extending. Gasket-plus-door-switch service is a 45-minute call that resolves most LXe "running long"
        complaints.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

